\frac{1}{1 - e^{-u}} = \sum_{k=0}^{\infty} e^{-ku} ?
0<x=e^{-u}<1
\sum_{k=0}^\infty x^k=\frac 1{1-x}
(e^{-u}-1)\sum_{i=0}^\infty e^{-ui}=e^{-u}\sum_{i=0}^\infty e^{-ui} - \sum_{i=0}^\infty e^{-ui}= \sum_{i=1}^\infty e^{-ui} - \sum_{i=0}^\infty e^{-ui}=-1.
\sum_{i=0}^\infty e^{-ui} = \frac{1}{1-e^{-u}}.
\mathbb{R}\{u\} > 0.
